--------------------------- THEMATIC SYNTHESIS -----------------------
Session 1 was about a thief learning what's worth keeping.
Kade started the session as a smooth, dangerous professional chasing the next rush. He ended it standing in a storage unit he'd converted into a home for a 10-year-old, terrified of the connection he'd built.
The compulsion is still there. The itch. The need to crack every lock, steal everything not nailed down, chase the edge until he falls. But now there's weight on the other side of the scale.
Sofia's joy. Mariana's hand. Rigs calling them "your family." Sable refusing to let him run from happiness. Marcus shaking his hand. Hector saying "Kids remember everything."
Kade is learning that some vaults open from the inside. That some things you can't pick your way into—you have to be let in. And that terrifies him more than any megacorp ever could.
He killed a man tonight. Threatened a child. Stole half a million in corporate assets. Recruited a dying man for a suicide mission.
He also bought rabbits. Made a home. Held someone's hand. Said "thank you" and meant it.
The Vessel is watching to see which version of Kade survives.
Revenge as survival. Survival through revenge. Building something while burning everything down.
The dawn is coming. Shiawase waits. Takeshi Mori has three weeks.
And somewhere in the dark, Kade's estranged daughter exists—unnamed, unspoken, carried like weight.
One day you'll pay. But not tonight.
Tonight, the rabbits are soft. The water is dark. The sneaky place is safe.
And Kade is learning what it means to have something worth keeping.
